# Observability Conventions

Every endpoint and service in Signal Lab must produce observability signals. This rule defines how.

## Prometheus Metrics

Metrics are exposed via `prom-client` at `GET /metrics` on the backend.

### Naming

- Use `snake_case` for all metric names
- Prefix domain metrics with the domain name: `scenario_runs_total`, `scenario_run_duration_seconds`
- Prefix generic HTTP metrics with `http_`: `http_requests_total`
- Counters MUST end with `_total`
- Histograms MUST end with `_seconds` (for durations) or `_bytes` (for sizes)

### Labels

- Keep label cardinality low (< 10 unique values per label)
- Standard labels for scenario metrics: `type` (scenario type), `status` (completed/failed)
- Standard labels for HTTP metrics: `method`, `path`, `status_code`
- NEVER use user IDs, request IDs, or timestamps as label values

### Required metrics for any new domain

1. A counter for total operations: `<domain>_<operation>_total`
2. A histogram for duration: `<domain>_<operation>_duration_seconds`

## Structured Logging

Logs are written as JSON to stdout and collected by Promtail â†’ Loki.

### Format

Every log entry MUST be a JSON object with these fields:

```json
{
  "timestamp": "ISO-8601",
  "level": "info|warn|error|debug",
  "message": "Human-readable description",
  "context": "ServiceName",
  "scenarioType": "success|system_error|...",
  "scenarioId": "cuid",
  "duration": 1234,
  "error": "Error message if applicable"
}
```

### Log levels

- `debug`: Internal state, only for development
- `info`: Successful operations (scenario completed, request served)
- `warn`: Slow requests (>2s), validation errors, degraded state
- `error`: Unhandled exceptions, system errors, integration failures

### Rules

- Log at least ONE entry per scenario run
- Include `scenarioType` and `scenarioId` in every scenario-related log
- Include `duration` (ms) for any timed operation
- NEVER log sensitive data (passwords, tokens, PII)
- NEVER use `console.log` â€” use NestJS Logger which outputs structured JSON

## Sentry

### When to capture

- `Sentry.captureException(error)` â€” for unhandled/system errors (5xx)
- `Sentry.addBreadcrumb(...)` â€” for validation errors and notable events
- NEVER capture expected business errors (404 for missing resources) as exceptions

### Context

- Set `extra` with `scenarioType`, `scenarioId` on Sentry scope
- Set `tags` for filterable dimensions: `scenario_type`, `environment`

## Grafana Dashboard

- Dashboard is provisioned via `monitoring/grafana/dashboards/`
- Datasources: Prometheus + Loki, provisioned via `monitoring/grafana/provisioning/`
- Every new metric SHOULD have a corresponding panel or be added to an existing one
